.pl 62













                     DEFINICON SYSTEMS, INC.



                    DSI-32 COPROCESSOR BOARD
                   & MS/PC DOS SYSTEM SOFTWARE



        










     INSTANT GRATIFICATION

.pa
Instant Gratification

Now  that you have received your DSI-32 card and assembled it (if 
it  was a kit) and you've plugged into your computer (please  see 
the instructions on installation), you probably want some instant 
gratification. Well, here it comes.

The  first  thing  you  should do is make a  backup  of  all  the 
distribution  disks  that came with your board and then  put  the 
originals in a safe place.  Next you should create a subdirectory 
for  your  DSI-32 development area.  Into this  subdirectory  you 
should copy all the files on your distribution disks.  Now we are 
ready  to  try the DSI-32 out,  part a) of this  discussion  will 
describe  how  to  try out the compilers and part b) is  for  the 
people that bought the DSI-32 without any compilers.

a) Lets assume for now that you purchased the C compiler, on your 
disk you will find a file called HELLO.C.  Type the file out  and 
you will see a simple print statement with the hello message.  We 
will now compile and run the test program.

     A>CC HELLO                    ; run the compiler

     A>AS HELLO                    ; assemble the compiler output

     A>LN FILE=HELLO               ; link the assembler output

At this stage you will find several new files on your disk,  they 
are:

     HELLO.A32      which is the output from the compiler,  it is 
                    in 32000 assembler code.
     HELLO.O32      which is the output from the assembler, it is 
                    the object file that is ready for linking.
     HELLO.E32      which  is the executable file that the linker 
                    produces,  this  is the file that is ready to 
                    run.
Now we are ready to run our test program,  all that is  necessary 
is to type:

     A>LOAD HELLO

If everything went ok, the hello message will be displayed on the 
console.  Now,  if  you want to play for a while just  experiment 
with changing the message. Note if you have the Pascal or Fortran 
compiler  instead  of  the C then all that changes  is  the  test 
filename,  it would be HELLO.P or HELLO.F and the compile command 
would be either:  A>PC HELLO or A>FC HELLO ,respectively. All the 
rest of the commands to assemble, link and load are the same.
.pa
b) Now lets assume that all you purchased was the DSI-32, with it 
comes  a  less elaborate (but object level compatible)  assembler 
and linker.  So in your case we supply an assembler test  program 
that says hello.  It is called HELLO.A32,  and uses direct system 
calls to display the hello message.  Let's go through the process 
of assembling and linking the test program.

     A>AS HELLO                    ; assemble the test program

     A>LN FILE=HELLO               ; link the test program

At this stage you will find several new files on your disk,  they 
are:

     HELLO.O32      which is the output from the assembler, it is 
                    the object file that is ready for linking.
     HELLO.E32      which  is the executable file that the linker 
                    produces,  this  is the file that is ready to 
                    run.

Now we are ready to run our test program,  all that is  necessary 
is to type:

     A>LOAD HELLO

If  everything went ok the hello message will be displayed on the 
console.  Now,  if  you want to play for a while just  experiment 
with changing the message. 

At  this stage you should be suitably gratified and it  would  be 
very wise for you to read the rest of the manual before you wreak 
havoc and get disillusioned.

